Detailed Description

Legup Hardware Module Representation.

GenerateRTL generates an RTLModule for a Verilog module, which has a one-to-one mapping with an LLVM function

Definition at line 2360 of file MultiCycle.cpp.

2362  {
2363 
2364  // If the destination is cur_state, then its driver is in an if condition.
2365  // Determine if the driver was used in the same state that it was
2366  // calculated,
2367  // or if there was cycle slack.
2368  //
2369  // The following example illustrates this case:
2370  //
2371  // In a BB, I have some register %a. The value of %a is used in a
2372  // series of computations (a path) and then the final output of
2373  // the path is wire %b.
2374  //
2375  // The wire %b is then used in a check like this:
2376  //
2377  // always @(posedge clk)
2378  // if (cur_state == LEGUP_X & b == 1'b1)
2379  // cur_state <= LEGUP_Y;
2380  //
2381  // The IR would look something like this:
2382  //
2383  // %a = xor i32 %foo, %bar
2384  // %b = add i32 %a, 4
2385  // %cmp = icmp eq i32 %b, 1
2386  // br i1 %cmp, label %Y, label %Z
2387  //
2388  // There is now a path between reg %a and reg cur_state, through the
2389  // wire %b. Note that this case only happens when transitioning
2390  // between BB (within a BB the states progress in a known order so
2391  // the "if" condition only involves the cur_state and memory controller
2392  // wait requests, not outside signals. Only for branches across BB do
2393  // we have these additional checks).
2394  //
2395  // Because this check runs every cycle (@posedge clk), it seems we
2396  // cannot multi-cycle the path from %a->cur_state.
2397  //
2398  // However, say we know from the scheduling that within the BB
2399  // where %b is calculated, %a is clocked in state 2, %b is calculated
2400  // in state 3, and %b is used in a branch in state 4 (e.g. the icmp
2401  // instruction b==1 is scheduled in state 4).
2402  //
2403  // Then, we know that between the state where %a is clocked and when
2404  // icmp b==1 is used, there is a certain cycle slack.
2405  //
2406  // Specifically, the code below does the following:
2407  //
2408  // For a register (e.g. %a), if %a or its descendant is used in a
2409  // branch or switch (or perhaps multiple), add cycle slack from %a
2410  // to cur_state equal to the min state difference between %a and
2411  // any downstream branch or switch (the first one found).
2412  //
2413  // Note that the MC paths always terminates at the FSM register. I never
2414  // handled the case of MC paths originating at the FSM registers
2415  // (I don't think I ever observed that, or if it can happen. It happens
2416  // in the case of terminating because of conditional branches).
2417  if (dst_name == "cur_state") {
2418  // path.front() is used in a conditional statement for cur_state
2419  Instruction *cond = path.front();
2420 
2421  int min_cycle_slack = 100;
2422  bool found_branch_use = false;
2423  // Check all the uses of this compare instruction.
2424  // Keep the minimum slack from the compare to a use branch.
2425  for (Value::user_iterator u = cond->user_begin(); u != cond->user_end();
2426  ++u) {
2427  Instruction *use = dyn_cast<Instruction>(*u);
2428  if (!use)
2429  continue;
2430  if (isa<BranchInst>(*use) || isa<SwitchInst>(*use)) {
2431  found_branch_use = true;
2432  // Get the cycle slack from cond to use.
2433  // Note: The convention num_cycles_in_path follows is root->src
2434  std::vector<Instruction *> tmp_path;
2435  tmp_path.push_back(use);
2436  tmp_path.push_back(cond);
2437  int state_difference = num_cycles_in_path(tmp_path);
2438  assert(state_difference >= 0);
2439  min_cycle_slack = std::min(min_cycle_slack, state_difference);
2440  }
2441  }
2442  assert(found_branch_use);
2443  multicycle_multiplier += min_cycle_slack;
2444  }
2445 }

2664  if (!LEGUP_CONFIG->getParameterInt("MULTI_CYCLE_ADD_THROUGH_CONSTRAINTS")) {
2665  return;
2666  }
2667 
2668  // First, there is no need to add -through constraints for multiple paths
2669  // sharing a src/dst register if the cycle slacks of all those paths are
2670  // the same. We can remove pairs for duplicate_src_dst_pairs in which all
2671  // of the path latencies are the same.
2672  prune_duplicate_src_dst_pairs_based_on_path_latency();
2673 
2674  // We'll write duplicate_src_dst_pairs to a file, so open it here
2675  // We'll also write pairs to a file which should have all their -through
2676  // constraints removed
2677  std::ofstream pairs_with_through_constraints_file;
2678  std::ofstream pairs_whose_through_constraints_must_be_removed_file;
2679  pairs_with_through_constraints_file.open(
2680  "src_dst_pairs_with_through_constraints.txt", std::fstream::app);
2681  pairs_whose_through_constraints_must_be_removed_file.open(
2682  "pairs_whose_through_constraints_must_be_removed.txt");
2683

2685  duplicate_src_dst_pairs_t::const_iterator pair_it =
2686  duplicate_src_dst_pairs.begin();
2687  duplicate_src_dst_pairs_t::const_iterator pair_e =
2688  duplicate_src_dst_pairs.end();
2689  for (; pair_it != pair_e; ++pair_it) {
2690  // Get the pair
2691  src_dst_pair_t src_dst_pair = *pair_it;
2692  std::string src = src_dst_pair.first;
2693  std::string dst = src_dst_pair.second;
2694 
2695  // Each pair has multiple paths associated with it.
2696  // Get this list of paths
2697  std::vector<path_t> paths;
2698  src_dst_pair_to_path_map_t::const_iterator mm_it_start =
2699  src_dst_pair_to_path_map.lower_bound(src_dst_pair);
2700  src_dst_pair_to_path_map_t::const_iterator mm_it_end =
2701  src_dst_pair_to_path_map.upper_bound(src_dst_pair);
2702 
2703  while (mm_it_start != mm_it_end) {
2704  paths.push_back(mm_it_start->second.first);
2705  ++mm_it_start;
2706  }
2707 
2708  // paths now contains all the paths associated with this pair.
2709  // Now we have to do some processing to get the signals which, if kept,
2710  // will
2711  // make all these paths unique.
2712 
2713  // Recall why this is being done: In some circuits (e.g. gsm) there are
2714  // multiple register-to-register paths with different latencies, because
2715  // the
2716  // paths are multi-cycled and span basic blocks. For example:
2717  //
2718  // SRC REGISTER
2719  // |
2720  // / \ .
2721  // / \ .
2722  // BB1 BB2
2723  // | |
2724  // \ /
2725  // |
2726  // DEST REGISTER
2727  //
2728  // Note this is not possible for 2 such paths in the same BB (since
2729  // src/dst will
2730  // always be in the same state regardless of intermediate wires). But
2731  // across BB
2732  // this happens a lot when dst is a PHI. BB1 can have latency 2, and BB2
2733  // can have
2734  // latency 20 (this also happens sometimes). If we multi-cycle both
2735  // these paths, then
2736  // we can set a multi-cycle constraint of 2 on the left path, and 20 on
2737  // the right.
2738  // We can set these different multi-cycle constraints by adding a
2739  // -through argument
2740  // to the .sdc constraint we print. Otherwise, if we don't use a
2741  // -through constraint,
2742  // then the two paths will have the same multi-cycle slack, which will
2743  // have to be
2744  // the minimum of the 2 slacks for functional correctness. This leads to
2745  // a large
2746  // critical path for some circuits. Using the minimum slack is the
2747  // default behavior
2748  // if MULTI_CYCLE_ADD_THROUGH_CONSTRAINTS is not set. If it is, then
2749  // -through
2750  // constraints are printed.
2751  //
2752  // But there's a problem: Quartus synthesis does not guarantee that the
2753  // intermediate
2754  // signals will be kept. Often all intermediate signals are synthesized
2755  // away, and
2756  // replaced with internal logiccells (e.g. Add3~53|cout,
2757  // LessThan2~9|combout). One
2758  // solution is to add synthesis keep to all these signals, but this adds
2759  // a lot of
2760  // delay and also takes very long in fit/STA (up to and including
2761  // Quartus 13.0sp1)
2762  //
2763  // Other than -through constraints + Synthesis keep, another solution
2764  // would be to
2765  // duplicate the registers. In the example above, we can make src
2766  // register 1 and
2767  // src register 2:
2768  //
2769  // SRC 1 SRC 2
2770  // | |
2771  // | |
2772  // | |
2773  // BB1 BB2
2774  // | |
2775  // \ /
2776  // |
2777  // DEST REGISTER
2778  //
2779  // Now separate constraints can be applied to these 2 paths (no -through
2780  // constraints needed)
2781  // But this becomes really complicated if we have something simple like:
2782  //
2783  // SRC REGISTER
2784  // |
2785  // BB1
2786  // |
2787  // / \ .
2788  // / \ .
2789  // BB2 BB3
2790  // | |
2791  // \ /
2792  // |
2793  // DEST REGISTER
2794  //
2795  // This is because now duplicating the register created 4 paths, instead
2796  // of 2.
2797  // I think therefore the best solution is to use -through constraints
2798  // and synthesis
2799  // keep, but only apply synthesis keep to some wires (as few as
2800  // possible).
2801  //
2802  // So say we have this:
2803  //
2804  // SRC
2805  // |
2806  // W1 (e.g. inside BB1)
2807  // |
2808  // /|\ .
2809  // / | \ .
2810  // / | \ .
2811  // | | |
2812  // W2 W3 W4
2813  // | | |
2814  // \ | /
2815  // \ | /
2816  // \|/
2817  // |
2818  // W5
2819  // |
2820  // DST
2821  //
2822  // Here, I just need to keep wires 2, 3, and 4. Wires {1,5} can be
2823  // synthesized away
2824  // because only {2,3,4} are needed to uniquely identify the paths.
2825  //
2826  // A more complicated example is this:
2827  //
2828  // SRC
2829  // |
2830  // W1
2831  // /|
2832  // W2 |
2833  // \|
2834  // W3
2835  // |
2836  // DST
2837  //
2838  // This might never happen so for cases like this (when there's no
2839  // unique
2840  // signal per path) I'll just print the minimum of all the paths.
2841  //
2842  // Note: a lot of this seems unnecessary, but it raises the Fmax of
2843  // blowfish,
2844  // gsm, and other circuits.
2845 
2846  std::vector<Instruction *> unique_signal_per_path;
2847  bool found_unique_inst_for_all_paths = true;
2848  for (unsigned path_index = 0; path_index < paths.size(); ++path_index) {
2849  Instruction *inst_unique_to_this_path =
2850  find_instruction_unique_to_path(path_index, paths);
2851 
2852  if (!inst_unique_to_this_path) {
2853  // Found a path without a unique instruction
2854  found_unique_inst_for_all_paths = false;
2855  break;
2856  } else {
2857  unique_signal_per_path.push_back(inst_unique_to_this_path);
2858  }
2859  }
2860 
2861  if (found_unique_inst_for_all_paths) {
2862  // Add all signals to the synth_keep set
2863  std::vector<Instruction *>::const_iterator inst_it =
2864  unique_signal_per_path.begin();
2865  std::vector<Instruction *>::const_iterator inst_e =
2866  unique_signal_per_path.end();
2867  for (; inst_it != inst_e; ++inst_it) {
2868  signals_to_keep.insert(verilogName(*inst_it));
2869  }
2870  // Also write this pair to a file
2871  pairs_with_through_constraints_file << src << "\t" << dst
2872  << std::endl;
2873  } else {
2874  // Default to the min constraint of all the paths
2875  // We'll do this using a separate post-processing script, which
2876  // modifies the .sdc file.
2877  // We also need to write the min constraint
2878  pairs_whose_through_constraints_must_be_removed_file
2879  << src << "\t" << dst << "\t"
2880  << src_dst_pair_to_min_slack[src_dst_pair] << std::endl;
2881  }
2882  }
2883 
2884  pairs_with_through_constraints_file.close();
2885  pairs_whose_through_constraints_must_be_removed_file.close();
2886 }

2017  {
2018 
2019  int source_state = alloc->get_registered_instruction_state(source);
2020 
2021  // If the source instruction is a PHI then its state is actually "-1"
2022  // in its Basic Block
2023  if (isa<PHINode>(source)) {
2024  source_state -= 1;
2025  }
2026 
2027  // If this source has latency > 0, then only the
2028  // first state was stored, so adjust source_state.
2029  //
2030  // Note: we subtract 1 from the # instruction cycles below
2031  // because the code assumes that an instruction scheduled in
2032  // state X has its value stored in a register at the end of
2033  // state X, and that this register can be read starting from
2034  // state X+1. E.g. if we have an adder in state 9, then this
2035  // means the adder's logic is in state 9 and so is its output
2036  // register. The register can be read starting from state 10.
2037  // Now, consider the example of a load, which returns 2 for
2038  // getNumInstructionCycles. Loads scheduled in state 9 will
2039  // be "ready to use" in state 11. Using the analogy of the
2040  // adder, it is as if the "load's logic" is in state 10 and the
2041  // load's register therefore is in state 10 as well, so the load
2042  // can be used starting state 11. Therefore we really only want
2043  // to extend the source state of the load by 1, not 2.
2044  if (Scheduler::getNumInstructionCycles(source) > 1) {
2045  source_state += (Scheduler::getNumInstructionCycles(source) - 1);
2046  }
2047 
2048  return source_state;
2049 }

1966  BasicBlock *prev_BB = NULL;
1967  int prev_instruction_end_state = -1;
1968  // We are traversing the path in reverse because it is root->src
1969  // but we want BBs from src->root
1970  for (std::vector<Instruction *>::reverse_iterator pi = path.rbegin();
1971  pi != path.rend(); ++pi) {
1972  Instruction *I = *pi;
1973  int start_state = alloc->get_registered_instruction_state(I);
1974  // If different BB, push the new BB onto the path
1975  if (I->getParent() != prev_BB) {
1976  prev_BB = I->getParent();
1977  bb_path.push_back(I->getParent());
1978  } else {
1979  // Otherwise, the previous instruction and this instruction
1980  // are in the same BB. However, the BB may have "looped around"
1981  // to itself, which happens in dfdiv.
1982  assert(prev_instruction_end_state >= 0);
1983  // MULTICYCLE_TODO: The BB can also loop back to itself if this
1984  // instruction is in the SAME state as the previous one (i.e.
1985  // not just in an earlier one), if the previous instruction is
1986  // not a direct pred of the current instruction. For now this
1987  // case is ignored as it seems very rare.
1988  if (start_state < prev_instruction_end_state) {
1989  bb_path.push_back(I->getParent());
1990  }
1991  }
1992  int end_state = start_state;
1993  if (Scheduler::getNumInstructionCycles(I) > 1) {
1994  end_state += Scheduler::getNumInstructionCycles(I);
1995  }
1996  prev_instruction_end_state = end_state;
1997  }
1998 }

Definition at line 1690 of file MultiCycle.cpp.

1690  {
1691  // Algorithm: Breadth-First Search with cycle checking
1692  // Start at dst and find all paths up to src
1693 
1694  // Set up BFS
1695  std::queue<BasicBlock *> frontier;
1696  frontier.push(dst);
1697 
1698  // Map each BB to its max distance so far
1699  // This map is also used to track already visited BB
1700  std::map<BasicBlock *, int> BB_to_dist;
1701  BB_to_dist[dst] = 0;
1702 
1703  // Do BFS
1704  while (!frontier.empty()) {
1705  // Pop next
1706  BasicBlock *curr = frontier.front();
1707  frontier.pop();
1708 
1709  // Loop over pred BBs of curr
1710  for (pred_iterator PI = pred_begin(curr), E = pred_end(curr); PI != E;
1711  ++PI) {
1712  BasicBlock *pred = *PI;
1713 
1714  // Get the distance from the start to pred along this path
1715  int new_dist = BB_to_dist[curr] + alloc->get_num_states_in_BB(pred);
1716 
1717  // If we've never seen this pred before, add its distance
1718  // and also add it to the queue
1719  if (BB_to_dist.find(pred) == BB_to_dist.end()) {
1720  BB_to_dist[pred] = new_dist;
1721  frontier.push(pred);
1722  }
1723  // Otherwise, check if we've found a longer path
1724  else if (new_dist > BB_to_dist[pred]) {
1725  BB_to_dist[pred] = new_dist;
1726  }
1727  }
1728  }
1729  // Return the distance from dst --> src, however ignore the
1730  // length of src itself
1731  int total_dist = BB_to_dist[src] - alloc->get_num_states_in_BB(src);
1732 
1733  // Corner case: In case the dist is ever 0 return 1, because we know
1734  // that src and dst have at least 1 BB between them
1735  total_dist = std::max(1, total_dist);
1736 
1737  return total_dist;
1738 }

1631  // Start at dst and find shortest path up to src
1632 
1633  // Two data structures, a priority queue of BB to search,
1634  // sorted by key (distance), and a reverse mapping (BB->dist)

1636  std::map<BasicBlock *, int> BB_to_dist;

1639  pq.insert(std::pair<int, BasicBlock *>(0, dst));
1640  BB_to_dist[dst] = 0;
1641

1643  while (!pq.empty()) {
1644  // Get the next lowest distance and its BB, and remove it from the pq
1645  int d = pq.begin()->first; // Guaranteed to be the lowest dist
1646  BasicBlock *curr =
1647  pq.begin()->second; // An arbitrary BB with this min dist
1648  pq.erase(pq.begin());

1651  if (curr == src) {
1652  break;
1653  }

1662  if (BB_to_dist.find(pred) == BB_to_dist.end()) {
1663  pq.insert(std::pair<int, BasicBlock *>(new_dist, pred));
1664  BB_to_dist[pred] = new_dist;
1665  continue;
1666  }
1667 
1668  // Otherwise, check if we've found a shorter path
1669  int old_dist = BB_to_dist[pred];

1671  pq.erase(std::pair<int, BasicBlock *>(old_dist, pred));
1672  pq.insert(std::pair<int, BasicBlock *>(new_dist, pred));
1673  BB_to_dist[pred] = new_dist;
1674  }
1675  }
1676  }

1678  // length of src itself

Definition at line 709 of file MultiCycle.cpp.

710  {
711  /*
712  * Note: an alternative way to remove registers would be to modify
713  * getOpNonConstant to return the wire instead of the register when
714  * initially constructing the module. However, some instructions have
715  * both register and wire uses. For example, an instruction may
716  * have uses in the same state (chain directly) and also in another BB
717  * (connected to its register).
718  *
719  * An alternative approach (this function) is to post-process the RTL
720  * module to remove connections to registers and replace them with
721  * direct connections to the wire.
722  */
723 
724  /* The LLVM DFG and RTL Data structure graphs are different.
725  For example consider the instruction %1 = add %2, %3 :
726 
727  LLVM Instructions RTL Signals
728 
729  %2 wire %3 wire
730  | |
731  %2 %3 %2 reg %3 reg
732  \ / \ /
733  \/ \ /
734  %1 \ /
735  "Add" RTLOp
736  |
737  |
738  %1 wire
739  |
740  %1 reg
741 
742  The inputs to this function are src and dst instructions, where
743  dst is "%1 = add %2, %3" and src is one of %2 or %3
744 
745  For example if src is %2 and dst is %1, this function aims to
746  modify the RTL above to directly connect the op to the wire src:
747 
748  %2 wire %3 wire
749  / | |
750  %2 reg | %3 reg
751  \ /
752  \ /
753  \ /
754  "Add" RTLOp
755  |
756  |
757  %1 wire
758  |
759  %1 reg
760 
761  Then if needed we call it again later for src = %3.
762  */
763 
764  // Get the RTL signal of dst (wire) and src (wire and reg)
765  RTLSignal *src_sig_w = rtl->findExists(verilogName(src));
766  RTLSignal *src_sig_r = rtl->findExists(verilogName(src) + "_reg");
767  RTLSignal *dst_sig_w;
768  if (isa<StoreInst>(*dst)) {
769  dst_sig_w = rtl->findExists(get_store_port_name(dst, src));
770  } else if (isa<LoadInst>(*dst)) {
771  dst_sig_w = rtl->findExists(get_load_port_name(dst));
772  } else {
773  dst_sig_w = rtl->findExists(verilogName(dst));
774  }
775 
776  if (!dst_sig_w) {
777  mc_debug() << "\n No signal, dst = " << *dst << ", "
778  << verilogName(dst) << "\n";
779  return;
780  }
781  if (!src_sig_w) {
782  mc_debug() << "\n No signal, src = " << *src << ", "
783  << verilogName(src) << "\n";
784  return;
785  }
786  if (!src_sig_r) {
787  return; // Src has no register signal, so there is nothing to remove
788  }
789  if (!src_sig_r->isReg()) {
790  return;
791  }
792 
793  mc_debug() << "\nRemoving reg from " << src_sig_w->getName() << " to "
794  << dst_sig_w->getName();
795 
796  bool found_correct_driver_signal = remove_intermediate_register_helper(
797  (RTLOp *)dst_sig_w, src_sig_w, src_sig_r);
798  if (!found_correct_driver_signal && isa<PHINode>(*dst)) {
799  found_correct_driver_signal =
800  remove_conditional_register(dst_sig_w, src_sig_w, src_sig_r);
801  assert(found_correct_driver_signal);
802  }
803 }

610  {
611  // Set up BFS
612  std::queue<RTLSignal *> frontier;
613  std::set<RTLSignal *> visited;
614  frontier.push(rtl_op_driver);
615  visited.insert(rtl_op_driver);
616 
617  // Do BFS
618  while (!frontier.empty()) {
619  // Pop next
620  RTLSignal *current = frontier.front();
621  frontier.pop();
622 
623  // Check each driver
624  unsigned num_drivers = get_num_signal_drivers_helper(current);
625  // Loop over drivers of current
626  for (unsigned i = 0; i < num_drivers; ++i) {
627  RTLSignal *driver = get_signal_driver_helper(current, i);
628  if (visited.find(driver) != visited.end()) {
629  continue;
630  }
631  visited.insert(driver);
632  frontier.push(driver);
633

635  // If the src is a register, connect to the wire instead
636  if (driver == src_sig_r) {
637  set_signal_operand_helper(current, i, src_sig_w);
638  }
639  // Found the correct source
640  return true;
641  }
642  }
643  }
644  return false;

1312  ram = alloc->getLocalRamFromValue(addr);

1314 
1315  if (ram && alloc->isRAMLocaltoFct(Fp, ram)) {
1316  std::string name = ram->getName();
1317 
1318  //errs() << "Connecting local RAM: " << ram->getName() << "\n";
1319 
1320  // convert byte address to word address
1321  RTLOp *wordAddr = rtl->addOp(RTLOp::Shr);
1322  wordAddr->setOperand(0, getOp(this->state, addr));
1323  int bytes = ram->getDataWidth() / 8;
1324  int ignore = (bytes == 0) ? 0 : (int) log2(bytes);
1325  wordAddr->setOperand(1, new RTLConst(utostr(ignore), RTLWidth(3)));
1326 
1327  connectSignalToDriverInState(rtl->find(name + "_address_" + port),
1328  wordAddr, this->state, instr);
1329  connectSignalToDriverInState(rtl->find(name + "_write_enable_" + port),
1330  ZERO, this->state, instr);
1331  connectSignalToDriverInState(loadWire, rtl->find(name + "_out_" + port),
1332  endState, instr);
1333  } else {
1334 
1335  loadStoreCommon(&I, addr);
1336  RTLSignal *memOut;
1337 
1338  // for parallel function
1339  // readdata needs to be taken from stored register
1340  bool isParallelFunction = Fp->hasFnAttribute("totalNumThreads");
1341  if (isParallelFunction) {
1342  memOut = rtl->find("memory_controller_out_stored_on_datavalid_" + port);
1343  } else {
1344  memOut = rtl->find("memory_controller_out_" + port);
1345  }
1346 
1347  RTLSignal *memWe = rtl->find("memory_controller_write_enable_" + port);
1348 
1349  connectSignalToDriverInState(memWe, ZERO, this->state, instr);
1350 
1351  // need to truncate memory_controller_out, which is usually
1352  // bigger than loadWire
1353  RTLOp *trunc = rtl->addOp(RTLOp::Trunc);
1354  trunc->setCastWidth(loadWire->getWidth());
1355  trunc->setOperand(0, memOut);
1356  connectSignalToDriverInState(loadWire, trunc, endState, instr);
1357  }
1358 }

1848  // Don't print the same constraints multiple times
1849  static std::set<std::string> reg_with_qsf_constraints;
1850 
1851  // Generate the sdc constraints
1852  // Note that for a multi-cycle path with slack N, the setup constraint
1853  // is N and the hold constraint is N-1. See the DATE 2015 paper for details.
1854  std::string setup_constraint = make_multicycle_constraint(
1855  src_name, dst_name, multicycle_multiplier, "setup", intermediate_path);
1856  std::string hold_constraint = make_multicycle_constraint(
1857  src_name, dst_name, multicycle_multiplier - 1, "hold",
1858  intermediate_path);
1859 
1860  // If -through constraints are being printed, add the constraints here.
1861  // Otherwise, they will be added below.
1862  if (LEGUP_CONFIG->getParameterInt("MULTI_CYCLE_ADD_THROUGH_CONSTRAINTS")) {
1863  sdc_constraints.push_back(setup_constraint);
1864  sdc_constraints.push_back(hold_constraint);
1865  }
1866 
1867  // How the constraints are printed depends on whether
1868  // MULTI_CYCLE_ADD_THROUGH_CONSTRAINTS is set.
1869 
1870  // If -through constraints will be printed, then at this point we've printed
1871  // the
1872  // entire path, including all -through constraints. In order for these
1873  // through
1874  // constraints to not be ignored, the intermediate wires need to not be
1875  // synthesized away.
1876  //
1877  // However, adding synthesis keep to every wire causes large delays and
1878  // large
1879  // increases in compile time. We can fix this by only adding synthesis keep
1880  // to
1881  // paths which require though constraints, and even in those paths only
1882  // adding
1883  // synthesis keep to the minimum number of signals required.
1884 
1885  // Check if the current pair of src/dst registers already has a multi-cycle
1886  // constraint
1887  bool pair_found_for_first_time = false;
1888  unsigned previous_multiplier = 0;
1889  src_dst_pair_t src_dst_pair(src_name, dst_name);
1890  if (src_dst_pair_to_path_map.find(src_dst_pair) !=
1891  src_dst_pair_to_path_map.end()) {
1892  duplicate_src_dst_pairs.insert(src_dst_pair);
1893  if (src_dst_pair_to_min_slack[src_dst_pair] > multicycle_multiplier) {
1894  previous_multiplier = src_dst_pair_to_min_slack[src_dst_pair];
1895  src_dst_pair_to_min_slack[src_dst_pair] = multicycle_multiplier;
1896  }
1897  // Also store the max slack
1898  if (src_dst_pair_to_max_slack[src_dst_pair] < multicycle_multiplier) {
1899  src_dst_pair_to_max_slack[src_dst_pair] = multicycle_multiplier;
1900  }
1901  }
1902  // Otherwise this is the first time we're seeing this src/dst pair
1903  else {
1904  src_dst_pair_to_min_slack[src_dst_pair] = multicycle_multiplier;
1905  src_dst_pair_to_max_slack[src_dst_pair] = multicycle_multiplier;
1906  pair_found_for_first_time = true;
1907  }
1908 
1909  // Add the current pair->path to our map
1910  src_dst_pair_to_path_map.insert(
1911  std::make_pair(src_dst_pair, std::make_pair(intermediate_path,
1912  multicycle_multiplier)));
1913 
1914  // Later, this map/set of all duplicates will be used to obtain a set of
1915  // instructions
1916  // to not synthesize away.
1917 
1918  // However, if -through constraints are NOT printed in this flow, then we
1919  // need
1920  // to instead print the constraint here only if it is the minimum cycle
1921  // constraint for this src/dst pair
1922  if (!LEGUP_CONFIG->getParameterInt("MULTI_CYCLE_ADD_THROUGH_CONSTRAINTS")) {
1923  // If this constraint has never been added, add it here with
1924  // the current multiplier
1925  if (pair_found_for_first_time) {
1926  sdc_constraints.push_back(setup_constraint);
1927  sdc_constraints.push_back(hold_constraint);
1928  }
1929  // Otherwise the constraint has been added. Replace it with this
1930  // constraint
1931  // if the multiplier is smaller
1932  else {
1933  // This constraint was previously added with a larger multiplier
1934  // Replace that constraint with this one
1935  if (multicycle_multiplier < previous_multiplier) {
1936  // Also replace in the vector
1937  std::string previous_setup = make_multicycle_constraint(
1938  src_name, dst_name, previous_multiplier, "setup",
1939  intermediate_path);
1940  std::string previous_hold = make_multicycle_constraint(
1941  src_name, dst_name, previous_multiplier - 1, "hold",
1942  intermediate_path);
1943 
1944  // Replace the setup constraint with this new one
1945  replace_sdc_constraint(sdc_constraints, previous_setup,
1946  setup_constraint);
1947  // Replace the hold constraint too
1948  replace_sdc_constraint(sdc_constraints, previous_hold,
1949  hold_constraint);
1950  }
1951  }
1952  }
1953 
1954  // Check if we should also print .qsf constraints to disable registers
1955  // with timing constraints to be merged
1956  print_qsf_constraints_to_disable_register_merging(
1957  src_name, dst_name, reg_with_qsf_constraints, qsf_constraints,
